---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="How to Keep Your Dev Machine Clean (Without Sacrificing Productivity)" description="Practical tips to stop your development machine from becoming a graveyard of forgotten tools. Version managers, containers, and the disposable environment approach.">
  <article class="blog-post">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="post-header">
        <time class="post-date">2026-04-03</time>
        <h1 class="post-title">How to Keep Your Dev Machine Clean (Without Sacrificing Productivity)</h1>
        <p class="post-meta">7 min read</p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-body">
        <p>
          I reformatted my laptop last year and it took an entire day to get everything back to a working state. Halfway through, I realized I was reinstalling tools I hadn't used in months. That's when I decided to change how I manage my dev environment.
        </p>
        <p>
          If your machine feels sluggish, if <code>which python</code> gives you existential dread, or if you have no idea what half the things in <code>/usr/local/bin</code> are -- this post is for you.
        </p>

        <h2>The Problem: Accumulation</h2>
        <p>
          Developers install things. A lot of things. And almost nobody uninstalls them afterward. Every tutorial, every side project, every "let me just try this real quick" leaves behind packages, config files, and background services.
        </p>
        <p>
          After a year or two, your machine is running services you forgot about, has conflicting versions of the same tool, and takes twice as long to boot.
        </p>

        <h2>Tip 1: Use Version Managers, Not Direct Installs</h2>
        <p>
          Never install programming languages directly. Always use a version manager:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Node.js:</strong> Use <code>fnm</code> or <code>nvm</code> instead of installing from nodejs.org</li>
          <li><strong>Python:</strong> Use <code>pyenv</code> instead of the system Python</li>
          <li><strong>Ruby:</strong> Use <code>rbenv</code> or <code>asdf</code></li>
          <li><strong>Java:</strong> Use <code>sdkman</code></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Version managers let you switch between versions per-project and make cleanup straightforward. When you no longer need a version, <code>nvm uninstall 16</code> and it's gone.
        </p>

        <h2>Tip 2: Prefer Project-Local Dependencies</h2>
        <p>
          Every <code>npm install -g</code> is a small mess you'll forget about later. Prefer local installs:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Use <code>npx</code> instead of global npm installs</li>
          <li>Use project-level virtual environments for Python (<code>python -m venv .venv</code>)</li>
          <li>Use <code>cargo install</code> with <code>--root</code> for Rust tools</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          When the project directory is deleted, the dependencies go with it.
        </p>

        <h2>Tip 3: Containers for Experimentation</h2>
        <p>
          This is the big one. If you want to try a new database, a new language, or a new tool -- don't install it on your host machine. Use a container.
        </p>
        <p>
          Want to try PostgreSQL 16? Don't install it. Run it in Docker:
        </p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> docker run --rm -p 5432:5432 -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=test postgres:16</pre>
        <p>
          When you <code>Ctrl+C</code>, it's gone. Your machine has no idea PostgreSQL was ever there.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a more general-purpose approach, tools like <a href="/fixitdev-site/tools/sandbox-cli">Sandbox CLI</a> let you spin up a full throwaway Linux environment via SSH:
        </p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> sandbox ssh
<span class="code-output">root@sandbox-7f3a:~#</span> apt-get install postgresql-16
<span class="code-comment"># experiment freely...</span>
<span class="code-prompt">root@sandbox-7f3a:~#</span> exit
<span class="code-output">Container destroyed.</span></pre>
        <p>
          Install whatever you want inside the container. When you disconnect, everything is cleaned up automatically. Your host machine stays untouched.
        </p>

        <h2>Tip 4: Audit What's Running in the Background</h2>
        <p>
          You'd be surprised how many background services accumulate. Check what's running:
        </p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-comment"># macOS</span>
<span class="code-prompt">$</span> launchctl list | grep -v com.apple
<span class="code-comment"># Linux</span>
<span class="code-prompt">$</span> systemctl list-units --type=service --state=running</pre>
        <p>
          I found MySQL, Redis, and a MongoDB instance that had been running since I tried them for a project eight months ago. All of them gone now.
        </p>

        <h2>Tip 5: Regular Cleanup Schedule</h2>
        <p>
          Set a calendar reminder every 3 months to:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Run <code>brew cleanup</code> (macOS) or check for orphaned packages</li>
          <li>Review <code>docker images</code> and <code>docker system prune</code></li>
          <li>Delete project directories you're no longer working on</li>
          <li>Check for unused version manager installs (<code>nvm ls</code>, <code>pyenv versions</code>)</li>
          <li>Review background services and disable what you don't need</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          15 minutes every quarter keeps things manageable.
        </p>

        <h2>Tip 6: Use Disposable Environments by Default</h2>
        <p>
          The nuclear option -- and honestly my favorite approach. Instead of trying to keep your machine clean retroactively, just stop installing things on it in the first place.
        </p>
        <p>
          My current setup: my host machine has Docker, my editor, a terminal, and <a href="/fixitdev-site/tools/sandbox-cli">Sandbox CLI</a>. That's it. When I need to test something, I run <code>sandbox ssh</code> and do it in a disposable container. The free tier gives you 3 containers per day, which covers most quick experiments. The Pro plan ($4.99/month) is unlimited if you want to go all-in on this approach.
        </p>
        <p>
          Is it a bit extreme? Maybe. But my laptop hasn't slowed down in a year, and <code>which python</code> only returns one result.
        </p>

        <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
        <p>
          A clean dev machine isn't about being obsessive -- it's about reducing the surface area for weird bugs, conflicts, and "why is this broken" debugging sessions. The less stuff on your host machine, the fewer things can go wrong.
        </p>
        <p>
          Start with version managers and local dependencies. Add containers for experimentation. If you want the simplest possible approach, check out <a href="/fixitdev-site/tools/sandbox-cli">Sandbox CLI</a> for instant throwaway environments.
        </p>
        <p>
          Your future self (and your laptop's SSD) will thank you.
        </p>

        <div class="post-cta">
          <a href="/fixitdev-site/tools/sandbox-cli" class="cta-link">Try Sandbox CLI -- keep your machine clean, effortlessly</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

